We can re-arrange this formula in this manner:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{OCF-(T \times D)}{1-T}&=(P-v)\times Q-FC
\end{aligned}$$

Moving the fixed cost to the other side of the equation, we have:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{OCF-(T \times D)}{1-T}+FC&=(P-v)\times Q
\end{aligned}$$

Finally, divide the whole equation by $(P-v)$ to isolate the quantity value:

$$\begin{aligned}
Q&=\dfrac{\frac{OCF-(T \times D)}{1-T}+FC}{P-v}
\end{aligned}$$

As we can see, this is the same relationship between the  quantity and the operating cashflow as the one shown in the exercise.

**c.** For this, we know that the accounting break-even occurs if the net income is zero. We know that if the net income is zero, then the outgoing cashflow and depreciation must be equal. This will give us:

$$\begin{aligned}
Q&=\dfrac{\frac{D-(T\times D)}{1-T}+FC}{P-v}
\end{aligned}$$

Factor out the numerator and we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
Q&=\dfrac{\frac{(1-T)\times D}{1-T}+FC}{P-v}\\
&=\dfrac{D+FC}{P-v}
\end{aligned}$$

As we can see, it is just the same as the original since the tax rate is cancelled at accounting break-even.
